[[sn:amato no Kuni Fudoki]]

{{DEFAULTSORT:Yamato no Kuni Fudoki}}
[[Category:Ja import failed]]

'''Yamato no Kuni Fudoki''' (Yamato Province 風土記) is the [[Fudoki]] of {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, compiled during the [[Nara period]]. The text survives only in the form of {{ill|fragments|ja|逸文|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, as outlined below.

== Mitonomaguwai (Three Union Marriage) ==
{{Quotation|
The ''Yamato no Kuni Fudoki'' states: "The {{ill|Amatsukami|ja|天津神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} no Mikoto and {{ill|Ishizukami|ja|石津神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} no Mikoto engaged in a union known as 'Mitonomaguwai'{{refnest|group="Note"|Referring to the union of man and woman.<ref name="taikeip421">''Fudoki,'' [[Iwanami Shoten]] Japanese Classical Literature Series 2, 14th edition, 1971 (1st edition, 1958), p.421, footnote.</ref>}}. They wandered in thought (''urabure''){{refnest|group="Note"|Meaning 'lost in thought.'<ref name="taikeip421" />}} and conversed face-to-face (''omogatari''){{refnest|group="Note"|Meaning 'direct conversation.'<ref name="taikeip421" />}}."
| ''Bishamondōbon Kokinshūchū''<ref name="taikei">''Fudoki,'' Japanese Classical Literature Series 2, [[Iwanami Shoten]].</ref>}}

== Ōkuchi no Magamikohara ==
{{Quotation|
Long ago, in the land of Asuka, there was an old wolf that devoured many people. The local villagers feared it and called it {{ill|Ōkuchi no Magami|ja|大口真神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ("Great-Mouthed True Deity"). The place where it lived was named Ōkuchi no Magamikohara{{refnest|group="Note"|An ancient name for the area near {{ill|Asuka Daibutsu|ja|飛鳥大仏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, also mentioned in the ''Man'yōshū.''<ref name="taikeip421" />}} as recorded in the Fudoki.
| ''Makurakotoba Shokumeishō (Middle)''<ref name="taikei" />}}

== Mitsue Jingū ==
{{Quotation|
The Fudoki states: "In the {{ill|Uda District, Nara|lt=Uda District|ja|宇陀郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in the village of Sasahata{{refnest|group="Note"|Now the Sasabata area of Hara Town, Yamabe 3.<ref name="taikeip421" />}}, stands the shrine of {{ill|Mitsue no Kami|ja|御杖の神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It does not enshrine the Great Spirit{{refnest|group="Note"|Meaning it does not enshrine the spirit of {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="taikeip421" />}}. {{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto|lt=Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|ja|倭姫命|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}} carried Amaterasu on her head and, with her as the staff, reached this place. After searching for the shrine's location for three months, she finally established the divine fields as {{ill|Kanjin|ja|神戸|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (lands belonging to the shrine)."
| ''Nihon Shoki Tsūshō, Volume 11''<ref name="taikei" />}}

