'''Yamato no Kuni Fudoki''' (Yamato Province 風土記) is the [[Fudoki]] of [[:en:Yamato Province|Yamato Province]], compiled during the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]]. The text survives only in the form of [[:en:Lost literary work|fragments]], as outlined below.
== Mitonomaguwai (Three Union Marriage) == {{Quotation| The ''Yamato no Kuni Fudoki'' states: "The {{ill|Amatsukami|ja|天津神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsukami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天津神・国津神}} no Mikoto and {{ill|Ishizukami|ja|石津神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishizukami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} no Mikoto engaged in a union known as 'Mitonomaguwai'{{refnest|group="Note"|Referring to the union of man and woman.<ref name="taikeip421">''Fudoki,'' [[:en:Iwanami Shoten|Iwanami Shoten]] Japanese Classical Literature Series 2, 14th edition, 1971 (1st edition, 1958), p.421, footnote.</ref>}}. They wandered in thought (''urabure''){{refnest|group="Note"|Meaning 'lost in thought.'<ref name="taikeip421" />}} and conversed face-to-face (''omogatari''){{refnest|group="Note"|Meaning 'direct conversation.'<ref name="taikeip421" />}}." | ''Bishamondōbon Kokinshūchū''<ref name="taikei">''Fudoki,'' Japanese Classical Literature Series 2, [[:en:Iwanami Shoten|Iwanami Shoten]].</ref>}}
== Ōkuchi no Magamikohara == {{Quotation| Long ago, in the land of Asuka, there was an old wolf that devoured many people. The local villagers feared it and called it {{ill|Ōkuchi no Magami|ja|大口真神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuchi no Magami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 真神}} ("Great-Mouthed True Deity"). The place where it lived was named Ōkuchi no Magamikohara{{refnest|group="Note"|An ancient name for the area near {{ill|Asuka Daibutsu|ja|飛鳥大仏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka Daibutsu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 飛鳥寺}}, also mentioned in the ''Man'yōshū.''<ref name="taikeip421" />}} as recorded in the Fudoki. | ''Makurakotoba Shokumeishō (Middle)''<ref name="taikei" />}}
== Mitsue Jingū == {{Quotation| The Fudoki states: "In the [[:en:Uda District, Nara|Uda District]], in the village of Sasahata{{refnest|group="Note"|Now the Sasabata area of Hara Town, Yamabe 3.<ref name="taikeip421" />}}, stands the shrine of {{ill|Mitsue no Kami|ja|御杖の神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mitsue no Kami|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. It does not enshrine the Great Spirit{{refnest|group="Note"|Meaning it does not enshrine the spirit of [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]].<ref name="taikeip421" />}}. [[:en:Yamatohime-no-mikoto|Yamatohime-no-Mikoto]] carried Amaterasu on her head and, with her as the staff, reached this place. After searching for the shrine's location for three months, she finally established the divine fields as {{ill|Kanjin|ja|神戸|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanjin|qq=}} (lands belonging to the shrine)." | ''Nihon Shoki Tsūshō, Volume 11''<ref name="taikei" />}}
